  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This is typically done by passing the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited and penalized under the Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China. The Chinese government has established a robust anti-money laundering (AML) legal framework, which includes the Anti-Money Laundering Law, to combat such financial crimes. Financial institutions and other entities are required to implement stringent AML measures, including customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and maintaining records.\n\nThe Chinese government is committed to maintaining financial order and combating illegal financial activities in accordance with the law. By enforcing strict anti-money laundering regulations, China aims to safeguard the integrity of its financial system and contribute to the global fight against financial crimes.",
